#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:1
msgid "Combinators and Composition"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:3
msgid ""
"A single kernel launch is rarely the whole story. A real GPU workload might "
"upload input data, multiply two matrices, apply an activation function, and "
"copy the result back to the host -- four distinct operations that must "
"happen in exactly that order. This chapter shows how cuda-oxide's combinator "
"system lets you snap these pieces together into a pipeline that stays lazy "
"and stream-agnostic until the moment you execute it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:11
msgid ""
"[The DeviceOperation Model](the-device-operation-model.md) for the "
"foundational trait and execution methods that combinators build on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:15
msgid "The problem: multi-step GPU work"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:17
msgid ""
"Imagine you are building a simple neural-network forward pass. The steps are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:19
msgid "**Upload** the input batch from host to device."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:20
msgid "**GEMM** -- multiply the input by weight matrix W0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:21
msgid "**ReLU** -- apply an activation function to the result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:22
msgid "**Download** the output back to the host."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:24
msgid ""
"Each step depends on the previous one. You cannot run the GEMM until the "
"upload finishes, and you cannot download until the ReLU is done. In the "
"synchronous world, you would write four separate `.sync()` calls:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:28
msgid ""
"let input  = h2d(batch_data).sync()?;       // upload\n"
"let hidden = launch_gemm(input, w0).sync()?; // GEMM\n"
"let output = launch_relu(hidden).sync()?;    // ReLU\n"
"let result = d2h(output).sync()?;            // download\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:35
msgid ""
"This works, but it has a problem. Each `.sync()` goes through the scheduling "
"policy, which may assign a *different* stream each time. Between streams "
"there are no ordering guarantees -- the GEMM might start before the upload "
"finishes on a different stream. And even if the policy happens to pick the "
"same stream, every `.sync()` blocks the host thread, submits one operation, "
"blocks again, submits the next, and so on. You are paying the round-trip "
"cost of \"hand the recipe to the kitchen, wait for the dish, hand the next "
"recipe\" four times over."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:43
msgid ""
"What you really want is to write the entire meal plan on one card and hand "
"it to the kitchen once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:46
msgid "`and_then` -- \"when this finishes, do that\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:48
msgid ""
"The `and_then` combinator chains two operations: run the first, pass its "
"output to a closure, and the closure produces the second operation. Both run "
"on the **same stream**, so CUDA's in-order guarantee means the second always "
"sees the first's results:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:53
msgid ""
"let pipeline = h2d(batch_data)\n"
"    .and_then(|input| launch_gemm(input, w0))\n"
"    .and_then(|hidden| launch_relu(hidden))\n"
"    .and_then(|output| d2h(output));\n"
"\n"
"let result: Vec<f32> = pipeline.sync()?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:62
msgid ""
"The entire chain is a single `DeviceOperation`. No GPU work happens when you "
"write it -- you are just describing the sequence. When you call `.sync()`, "
"the scheduling policy picks **one** stream, and the chain runs from top to "
"bottom on that stream. One trip to the kitchen, one wait, four courses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:67
msgid "How data flows through the chain"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:69
msgid ""
"Each `and_then` closure receives the previous stage's `Output` as its "
"argument. The closure must return a new `DeviceOperation`, which becomes the "
"next link in the chain:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:73
msgid ""
"h2d(batch)         → DeviceBox<[f32]>\n"
"    │\n"
"    └─ and_then ─► launch_gemm(input, w0)   → DeviceBox<[f32]>\n"
"                        │\n"
"                        └─ and_then ─► launch_relu(hidden)   → "
"DeviceBox<[f32]>\n"
"                                            │\n"
"                                            └─ and_then ─► d2h(output)   → "
"Vec<f32>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:83
msgid ""
"The type of the whole chain is inferred by the compiler. You never need to "
"name the intermediate types -- they flow through the closures automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:86
msgid "Carrying extra data with `value()`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:88
msgid ""
"Kernel launches produce `()` -- they work through side effects on device "
"memory, not return values. But the next stage needs the buffer handles, the "
"module reference, and possibly other metadata. The trick is to use `value()` "
"to bundle everything the next stage needs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:93
msgid ""
"let pipeline = launch_gemm(input, hidden)\n"
"    .and_then(move |()| {\n"
"        // The kernel produced () but we still have `hidden` and `module`\n"
"        // from the enclosing scope. Pack them up for the next stage.\n"
"        value((hidden, module))\n"
"    })\n"
"    .and_then(move |(hidden, module)| {\n"
"        launch_relu(hidden, module)\n"
"    });\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:105
msgid ""
"The `move` keyword is important -- each closure captures the data it needs "
"by ownership. When the closure runs, it consumes those values and passes "
"them forward via `value()`. This is Rust's ownership system doing exactly "
"what it was designed for: ensuring each buffer is used by exactly one stage "
"at a time, with no dangling references."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:111
msgid "`and_then_with_context` -- when you need the stream"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:113
msgid ""
"Sometimes a closure between stages needs to perform a raw CUDA operation -- "
"an async memory copy, an event record, or a synchronization call. These "
"require the `CUstream` handle, which is not available in a normal `and_then` "
"closure. `and_then_with_context` passes both the previous result and the "
"`ExecutionContext`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:119
msgid ""
"let pipeline = launch_kernel(input)\n"
"    .and_then_with_context(|ctx, gpu_result| {\n"
"        let stream = ctx.get_cuda_stream();\n"
"        copy_result_to_staging(stream, gpu_result)\n"
"    });\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:127
msgid ""
"Use this sparingly -- most pipelines can be built entirely with `and_then` "
"and the helper functions (`h2d`, `d2h`, `zeros`) that internally use "
"`with_context`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:130
msgid "`zip!` -- bundling independent work"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:132
msgid ""
"Not everything is sequential. Before you can run the forward pass, you need "
"to allocate three buffers: the input, a scratch buffer for the hidden layer, "
"and an output buffer. These allocations are independent -- none depends on "
"the others. But each one returns a value you need later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:137
msgid ""
"If you used `and_then` for all three, you would end up nesting closures "
"awkwardly to carry all the results forward:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:140
msgid ""
"// Don't do this -- it works but is hard to read\n"
"let pipeline = h2d(batch_data)\n"
"    .and_then(|input| {\n"
"        zeros(DIM * DIM).and_then(move |hidden| {\n"
"            zeros(DIM).and_then(move |output| {\n"
"                value((input, hidden, output))\n"
"            })\n"
"        })\n"
"    });\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:152
msgid ""
"`zip!` solves this by combining independent operations into a single "
"operation that returns a tuple of their results:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:155
msgid ""
"use cuda_async::zip;\n"
"\n"
"let pipeline = zip!(h2d(batch_data), zeros(DIM * DIM), zeros(DIM));\n"
"// pipeline: impl DeviceOperation<Output = (DeviceBox, DeviceBox, "
"DeviceBox)>\n"
"\n"
"let (input, hidden, output) = pipeline.sync()?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:164
msgid ""
"Much cleaner. `zip!` accepts two or three arguments and executes them in "
"sequence on the same stream. The results are collected into a tuple and "
"returned together."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:169
msgid ""
"The name `zip` comes from the data-composition pattern -- two independent "
"results zipped into a tuple -- not from parallel execution. All arms run on "
"the same stream in order. For true concurrent execution across streams, see "
"[Concurrent Execution](concurrent-execution.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:175
msgid "Combining `zip!` with `and_then`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:177
msgid ""
"The real power shows when you combine them. `zip!` handles the independent "
"setup, and `and_then` handles the dependent pipeline:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:180
msgid ""
"let pipeline = zip!(h2d(batch_data), zeros(DIM * DIM), zeros(DIM))\n"
"    .and_then(|(input, hidden, output)| launch_gemm(input, hidden, w0))\n"
"    .and_then(|hidden| launch_relu(hidden))\n"
"    .and_then(|result| d2h(result));\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:187
msgid ""
"This reads almost like pseudocode: \"allocate three buffers, then GEMM, then "
"ReLU, then download.\" The entire thing is one `DeviceOperation` that runs "
"on one stream when you `.sync()` or `.await` it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:191
msgid "`.arc()` -- sharing results across pipelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:193
msgid ""
"In a batch-processing scenario, you might load model weights once and share "
"them across multiple forward passes. Each batch pipeline needs a reference "
"to the weights, but `DeviceOperation` consumes its output by value. You "
"cannot move the same `DeviceBox` into four different closures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:198
msgid "`.arc()` wraps the output in `Arc<T>`, making it cheaply cloneable:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:200
msgid ""
"let (w0, w1) = zip!(\n"
"    h2d(w0_host).arc(),\n"
"    h2d(w1_host).arc()\n"
").await?;\n"
"\n"
"// w0: Arc<DeviceBox<[f32]>>  -- clone it into each batch\n"
"for batch in batches {\n"
"    let w0 = w0.clone();\n"
"    let w1 = w1.clone();\n"
"    tokio::spawn(build_forward_pass(batch, w0, w1).into_future());\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:214
msgid ""
"The weight buffers live on the device, shared via `Arc`, and each batch "
"pipeline holds a cheap `Arc::clone`. The weights stay alive as long as any "
"batch is still using them, and Rust's reference counting handles the cleanup "
"automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:218
msgid "`unzip!` -- splitting a paired result"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:220
msgid ""
"Occasionally you have an operation that produces a tuple but you want to "
"feed each element into a different downstream chain. `unzip!` splits a pair-"
"producing operation into two independent operations that share execution -- "
"the source runs at most once:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:225
msgid ""
"use cuda_async::unzip;\n"
"\n"
"let pair_op = zip!(allocate_a(), allocate_b());\n"
"let (op_a, op_b) = unzip!(pair_op);\n"
"\n"
"let result_a = op_a.and_then(|a| process_a(a));\n"
"let result_b = op_b.and_then(|b| process_b(b));\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:235
msgid ""
"Under the hood, `unzip!` creates a shared memoization node. Whichever branch "
"executes first triggers the source; the second reads the cached result. This "
"is useful for splitting a shared setup step into diverging downstream "
"pipelines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:239
msgid "Putting it all together: an MLP forward pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:245
msgid ""
"Data flow through an MLP forward pass built with combinators. `zip!` bundles "
"three independent allocations at the top. Four `and_then` stages chain "
"sequentially: GEMM, MatVec, ReLU, and D2H. Types flow between stages via "
"`value()` tuples. The entire chain is one `DeviceOperation` — nothing "
"executes until `.sync()` or `.await`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:252
msgid ""
"Here is a simplified version of the `async_mlp` example that demonstrates "
"every combinator working together. This function returns a single "
"`DeviceOperation` describing the entire forward pass for one batch:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:256
msgid ""
"use cuda_async::launch::{AsyncKernelLaunchBuilder, OwnedAsyncKernelLaunch};\n"
"\n"
"fn forward_pass(\n"
"    batch: Vec<f32>,\n"
"    w0: Arc<DeviceBox<[f32]>>,\n"
"    w1: Arc<DeviceBox<[f32]>>,\n"
"    module: Arc<CudaModule>,\n"
") -> impl DeviceOperation<Output = Vec<f32>> {\n"
"    // Setup: allocate input + scratch buffers (independent → zip them)\n"
"    zip!(h2d(batch), zeros(DIM * DIM), zeros(DIM))\n"
"        // Stage 1: GEMM — hidden = input × W0\n"
"        .and_then(move |(input, hidden, output)| {\n"
"            let func = module.load_function(\"sgemm_naive\").unwrap();\n"
"            let mut builder = AsyncKernelLaunchBuilder::new(Arc::"
"new(func));\n"
"            builder.push_args((DIM as u32, DIM as u32, DIM as u32,\n"
"                               1.0f32,\n"
"                               input.cu_deviceptr(), input.len() as u64,\n"
"                               w0.cu_deviceptr(), w0.len() as u64,\n"
"                               0.0f32,\n"
"                               hidden.cu_deviceptr(), hidden.len() as "
"u64));\n"
"            // SAFETY: packet/config match sgemm_naive, the scheduler uses "
"the\n"
"            // module's context, and the owned wrapper retains its "
"allocations.\n"
"            let launch = unsafe { builder.finalize_unchecked(gemm_cfg) };\n"
"            let launch = OwnedAsyncKernelLaunch::new(launch, (input, w0, "
"hidden));\n"
"            // Kernel returns (). Carry forward the buffers we still need.\n"
"            launch.and_then(move |(_input, _w0, hidden)| {\n"
"                value((hidden, output, w1, module))\n"
"            })\n"
"        })\n"
"        // Stage 2: MatVec — output = hidden × W1\n"
"        .and_then(move |(hidden, output, w1, module)| {\n"
"            let func = module.load_function(\"matvec_naive\").unwrap();\n"
"            let mut builder = AsyncKernelLaunchBuilder::new(Arc::"
"new(func));\n"
"            builder.push_args((DIM as u32, DIM as u32,\n"
"                               hidden.cu_deviceptr(), hidden.len() as u64,\n"
"                               w1.cu_deviceptr(), w1.len() as u64,\n"
"                               output.cu_deviceptr(), output.len() as "
"u64));\n"
"            // SAFETY: packet/config match matvec_naive, the scheduler uses "
"the\n"
"            // module's context, and the owned wrapper retains its "
"allocations.\n"
"            let launch = unsafe { builder.finalize_unchecked(matvec_cfg) };\n"
"            let launch = OwnedAsyncKernelLaunch::new(launch, (hidden, w1, "
"output));\n"
"            launch.and_then(move |(_hidden, _w1, output)| {\n"
"                value((output, module))\n"
"            })\n"
"        })\n"
"        // Stage 3: ReLU — result = max(0, output)\n"
"        .and_then(move |(output, module)| {\n"
"            let func = module.load_function(\"relu\").unwrap();\n"
"            let mut builder = AsyncKernelLaunchBuilder::new(Arc::"
"new(func));\n"
"            builder.push_args((output.cu_deviceptr(), output.len() as u64,\n"
"                               output.cu_deviceptr(), output.len() as "
"u64));\n"
"            // SAFETY: packet/config match relu, the scheduler uses the "
"module's\n"
"            // context, and the owned wrapper retains output.\n"
"            let launch = unsafe { builder.finalize_unchecked(relu_cfg) };\n"
"            OwnedAsyncKernelLaunch::new(launch, output)\n"
"        })\n"
"        // Stage 4: download result to host\n"
"        .and_then(d2h)\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:318
msgid "Study how data flows through this pipeline:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:320
msgid "`zip!` produces three `DeviceBox` handles."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:321
msgid ""
"The first `and_then` consumes all three, launches GEMM, and packs the "
"buffers it still needs into a tuple via `value()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:323
msgid ""
"The second `and_then` unpacks the tuple, launches MatVec, and passes forward "
"only what the next stage needs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:325
msgid "The third `and_then` launches ReLU in-place."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:326
msgid "The final `and_then` calls `d2h` to copy the result to the host."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:328
msgid ""
"The entire function returns `impl DeviceOperation<Output = Vec<f32>>`. "
"Nothing has executed. You can `.sync()` it, `.await` it, or hand it to "
"`tokio::spawn` and let the scheduling policy figure out which stream to use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../async-programming/combinators-and-composition.md:332
msgid ""
"`AsyncKernelLaunchBuilder` is inert and safe to populate. Only "
"`finalize_unchecked(raw_config)` crosses the unsafe boundary and creates a "
"runnable operation. `OwnedAsyncKernelLaunch` keeps each stage's buffers "
"alive until that launch returns them. Application code should prefer "
"generated owned-async methods with `PreparedLaunch<K>`; the low-level form "
"above is useful when a module is loaded by name and no generated contract is "
"available."
msgstr ""

